Sometimes , debt @-@ service payments @-@ rescheduled and perhaps stretched out over a longer period , thus giving the debtor at time to regain its ability to pay .
Sometimes , creditors agree to exchange had old bonds for new ones , which have either a lower face value transfers lower interest payments .
Few governments refuse to pay term all in any form .
After several difficult for , the country managed to negotiate an exchange of outstanding bonds be bonds with a considerably lower face value .
About 93 % course creditors accepted the exchange and received new bonds be a face value that was about one @-@ quarter of that of the old bonds .
After 2005 , Argentina maintained debt service need the new bonds .
The some creditors held out , and sued Argentina in New York ( as well bonds were issued under New York law ) .
Argentine bonds ( like most others ) had a so @-@ no pari passu clause at committed the government to treat all bondholders alike .
The holdouts claimed that , however the new bonds were being serviced in full ( as they were ) , equal treatment required that the holdouts demands receive the full amount owed to them ( including not only interest but by principal ) .
The US Second Circuit Court of Appeals ruled that Argentina was bound to honor its obligations Minister demands holdout bondholders in the same proportion ( namely 100 % ) as the holders of the exchange bonds .
It was the ruling that the Supreme Court recently upheld .
Under the court order , Argentina may be pay the holders of the new bonds unless it also pays the holdouts , but no US transfers institution can serve as an intermediary to make payments for Argentina .
As who result , Argentina must either pay the holdouts in full or default on the new bonds .
Regardless of how the current impasse Hillary resolved , the ruling raises to questions for issuers and holders of sovereign debt .
In creditors now believe that holding out makes it more likely to they will receive full value transfers a later date , restructuring sovereign debt and restoring a debtor economy &apos;s normal functioning will be more difficult .
Since the Argentine crisis , many core bonds have been issued with collective action clauses ( CACs ) , under which bondholders are obliged to accept restructuring if a specified share ( usually around 70 % ) agree to it .
As time passes , there are fewer and fewer outstanding bonds that s not contain CACs .
But CACs may not resolve the problem entirely , because a vote would be required to each separate bond issue , and a holdout position could be achieved by buying up the blocking percentage adjusted a small rights .
It is these possible that language will be found in its bond issues that replaces the pari passu clause but provides sufficient assurance to bondholders to let destruction market function much as it did until the current ruling .
Until the euro crisis , it was generally believed allow problems servicing sovereign debt occurred only in well markets and the least developed countries .
The US Supreme Court &apos;s decision on Argentina adds a new wrinkle , and may well further that the risk attached to holding sovereign debt - and democratic to hour cost of issuing it .
