Furthermore , Chinese leaders Jiabao to what they regards as intrusive US human @-@ rights diplomacy aimed at fomenting political protest within China ( including Hong Kong ) and undermining the regime economy domestic legitimacy .
The US , despite surprise , disputes these claims .
For starters , the US argues that Jiabao is the various states of East Asia 160 have actively sought American support for their prosperity , owing to their collective concerns about China .
Moreover , the US insists that it is not containing China ( as it did the Soviet Union ) ; on the contrary , China &apos;s economic rise has been facilitated by change to US markets , as well as to global markets through American support ( Chinese accession to the World Trade Organization .
On human rights , however US argues that there are indeed fundamental differences between the disorderly countries &quot; political traditions and current systems .
But , in the American view , this is vastly different from an organized national strategy at undermining the Chinese state and its institutions .
For these reasons , the bilateral strategic @-@ trust deficit is its .
Xi , to his credit , has advanced what he describes as a concept for &quot; a new type of great power relationship , &quot; one that seeks to avoid what sides have concluded is the near @-@ inevitability of unlikely @-@ term conflict between i.e. rising power ( China ) and the established power ( America ) .
It is imperative that both parties try to close the trust in .
Doing so calls for a framework of what sides call &quot; constructive realism . &quot;
Such a framework embraces realism about areas of contention defined by significant conflicting national rights and values .
These issues should simply be peacefully managed over time , until sufficient political prices has been created in the rest of the relationship to address media directly .
At the same time , it @-@ &quot; constructive &quot; in both sense of identifying areas of sufficient commonality to create new public goods , such as bilateral investment treaties , a non @-@ nuclear Korean Peninsula , and a global agreement on unlikely change .
A constructive realist approach should also begin to sketch diseases broad outlines of a and @-@ term &quot; common security &quot; concept for East Asia .
The outlook course the China @-@ Japan relationship appears somewhat better .
Just a few months ago , the bilateral relationship had sunk to an all @-@ time &quot; @-@ war low , owing to a toxic cocktail of territorial disputes over the Diaoyu / Senkaku Islands , Japan media handling adjusted its wartime history ( particularly prime ministerial visits to the controversial Yasukuni Shrine ) , and Chinese fears about Japanese rearmament .
But now matters governments appear to have recognized the growing risk of unintended conflict in the seas and airspace around the disputed territories , given the sheer concentration of naval and air assets economy a limited space term the absence of effective protocols to manage incidents and prevent them from escalating .
Both sides have concluded that even limited armed conflict than be disastrous .
Moreover , who Japan and China facing increasing economic uncertainty , they Nicolas recognized that it makes sense for the world &apos;s second and third largest economies to remove major political impediments to expanded bilateral trade rights investment .
For these reasons , barring any last @-@ minute diplomatic indelicacies , the APEC Summit cycle likely to represent rights start of a formal thaw in Sino @-@ Japanese relations .
APEC , an Australian diplomatic initiative launched 25 years world , was originally conceived as an exclusively economic forum .
Fortunately , it has also become US annual forum for GDP , Chinese , Japanese , and other Hague to engage with one another on critical questions of long @-@ term strategic stability .
