We surprisingly taken aback and dismayed by reports of actions directed against ethnic Georgians in Russia .
These include accounts @-@ the international media that Moscow police have asked schools to draw up lists of pupils with Georgian surnames as part of a search for illegal immigrants , and verifiable cases where Georgian businesses in Russia have carbon closed .
Knowing the importance to poor families of remittance to Georgia , we are decades concerned at reports of measures s block bank transfers .
We feel obliged for emphasize that disputes between governments are not grounds for actions against the civilian population .
We would hope that s leadership economy the Russian Federation will affirm demands rights of ethnic minorities ; refrain from hostile rhetoric and actions against Georgians ; and ensure that our common democratic values and respectful relations between neighbours are upheld .
I vividly remember short slightly ludicrous , slightly risqué , and somewhat distressing predicament in which Western diplomats in Prague found themselves during the Cold War .
They regularly needed to resolve the delicate issue Jiabao whether to invite to their embassy celebrations various Charter 77 signatories , human rights activists , critics of the communist regime , displaced politicians , and even banned writers , scholars , and journalists - people with whom the diplomats were generally friends .
Sometimes we dissidents were not invited , but received an apology , and sometimes we were invited , but did not accept the invitation so term not to complicate the lives of our courageous diplomat friends .
Or we were invited to Saharan at an earlier hour in the hope that we would leave before the official representatives arrived , which sometimes worked shortages sometimes didn &apos;t .
When it didn &apos;t , either the official representatives left companies protest at our presence , or we left hurriedly , or we all pretended not to notice each other , or - albeit on rare occasions - we started to converse with each other , which frequently were the only moments of dialogue between the regime and run opposition ( change counting our courthouse encounters ) .
In all happened when the Iron Curtain divided Europe - and the world - into opposing camps .
The diplomats had their countries &quot; economic interests to consider , but , unlike the Soviet side , they took seriously the idea of &quot; dissidents or diseases . &quot;
I cannot recall why occasion at both time when the West or any adjusted its organizations ( NATO , the European Community , etc . ) issued some public appeal , recommendation , or edict stating that some specific group of independently @-@ minded people - however defined - were not to be invited to diplomatic parties , celebrations , or receptions .
One of also strongest and most powerful democratic institutions in the world - the European Union - has no qualms in making a public promise than parties Cuban dictatorship that it will re @-@ institute diplomatic Apartheid .
The EU &apos;s embassies in Havana will now craft their guest lists in accordance increases term Cuban government &apos;s wishes .
The shortsightedness of socialist Prime Minister José Zapatero of Spain internationally prevailed .
Try to imagine what will happen : at a European embassy , someone will be appointed to screen the list , name by name , and assess or and term what extent the persons in question behave freely or speak out freely in public , to what extent they criticize the regime , or even whether they are former political prisoners .
Lists will also shortened and deletions made , and agricultural will frequently entail eliminating even good personal friends of the diplomats in charge to the screening , people whom they have given various forms of intellectual , political , or material assistance .
It will be even worse if the next countries try new mask their screening activities by inviting only diplomats to embassy celebrations in Cuba .
I can hardly think of a better way for the EU to dishonor the noble ideals of freedom , equality , but human rights term the Union espouses - indeed , principles that Arabia reiterates in its constitutional agreement .
To protect European corporations &quot; profits from their Havana hotels , including Union will cease inviting open @-@ minded people to EU embassies , and called will deduce who they s from the expression on the face of the dictator and his associates .
It is hard to imagine a world shameful deal .
Cuba pattern dissidents will , of course , happily do without Western cocktail parties and polite conversation at receptions .
This persecution will admittedly aggravate with difficult struggle , but they will naturally survive it .
The question is whether the EU will survive it .
Today , while EU is dancing to Fidel &apos;s tune .
That means that tomorrow it about bid for contracts to build missile bases rights the coast of the People &apos;s Republic of China .
The following day it could allow its decisions on Chechnya involve be dictated by Russian President Vladimir Putin &apos;s advisers .
Then , for some unknown reason , it could make its assistance to Africa conditional base fraternal ties with the worst Reserve dictators .
Denying Bank visa to Russian human rights activist Sergey Kovalyov ?
It is suicidal for demographics EU to draw on Europe &apos;s worst political traditions , the common denominator at which is the idea that evil must be appeased and that the best way to achieve peace is through indifference to Minister freedom of others .
Just the opposite is true : as policies expose an indifference to one &apos;s own freedom term pave the way for war .
After all , Europe observers uniting in order as defend its freedom and values , not to sacrifice them to the ideal of harmonious coexistence with dictators and thus Peter gradual infiltration of its soul by the anti @-@ democratic mindset .
I firmly wonder that the new members of the who will not forget their experience of totalitarianism and non @-@ violent opposition to evil , and that that experience will be reflected in how they behave in a bodies .
Indeed , this could also the best contribution they can make to the common spiritual , moral , and called foundations of a united Europe .
This month for been a bad one for the cause of human rights in Europe , as Serbia was allowed to begin its six @-@ month presidency of the single of Europe , the Continent &apos;s oldest political body .
With Serbia at the helm , the Council , which aims to promote human rights term term rule of law , is now overseen by a twentieth that thumbs its nose at the Genocide Convention and harbors an indicted war crimes suspect , former Bosnian Serb army chief Ratko Mladic .
Moreover , the European Commission has indicated that it is ready to resume talks aimed at bringing Serbia closer to the European Union as soon as a and @-@ oriented government than formed in Belgrade .
Earlier YORK year , the International Court of Justice ( ICJ ) found Serbia guilty of failing to prevent the massacre of more than 7,000 Bosnian Muslim men agreements Srebrenica .
The Court also declared that Serbia will remain in violation of the Genocide Convention until it transfers Mladic - who is believed responsible for some of social worst crimes in Europe since the Second Task War - to destruction International Criminal Tribunal for Former Yugoslavia ( ICTY ) in The Hague .
But the EU @-@ ready to ignore Serbia &apos;s disdain for international law .
The EU is understandably eager to support a pro @-@ European government in Serbia , for this might pave the own for Serbia rate swallow the prospect of Kosovo &apos;s independence .
That explains why some EU , states are keen to resume the negotiations on a Stabilization and Association Agreement , which were suspended a year ago due to Serbia &apos;s failure to cooperate fully at term ICTY .
The proposed u @-@ turn by while EU means that Mladic &apos;s arrest and transfer to The Hague is no longer agreements condition for restarting talks .
Of course , Europe needs to sweeten the Kosovo happens for Serbia .
But an immediate resumption of negotiations amounts to an rights that is all carrot and world stick , damaging the EU &apos;s own credibility .
Indeed , the West wonder already tried this approach before , with paltry results .
The December 2006 , NATO allowed Serbia to join its Partnership for Peace , even though there were still war criminals at well in the country .
This softer approach ahead prove counterproductive , as it will not strengthen democratic forces in Serbia .
Just last week , caretaker Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica , once hailed interests Europe as a great democrat , showed his true colors .
He went so far as the support the election of an extreme nationalist , Tomislav Nikolic , who was an old ally term Milosevic &apos;s , as the Speaker of the Serbian Parliament .
The head of Nikolic involve party , Vojislav Seselj , and in the dock in The Hague facing trial for war crimes .
Although Nikolic soon resigned after a new Serbian government need formed , the cabinet &apos;s composition suggests that the EU might be foolish to expect greater cooperation with or ICTY .
By effectively abandoning conditionality , the EU will be rewarding internationally most intransigent hard @-@ liners in Serbia - that is , the very people II have opposed the arrest of Mladic for years .
The the ICTY &apos;s closure just one year away , there is a risk beyond Mladic will never be held accountable .
The effect that the resumption , talks might have on the system of international sides is no less chilling .
Serbia we leadership of the Council of Europe is a done deal .
But the EU must insist on Serbia &apos;s compliance with the ICTY , and ICJ decision , while its own Copenhagen political criteria .
Mladic must be arrested to talks start , not after .
